5eb9571ef8e545851508b968~799~3446~0~1~"Early walk round the local streets today as I had a very early call. Then some pilates stretches. Then started the week with a pick me up from the community that is @markshayler ‚Äòs weekly communion.  I feel better now and ready to start the week in a positive way.

Last night.  I read a really long post by a doctor advising people to be sensible.  Saying that the government funded Bank Holiday that had gone on for weeks had to end.  That we had to start dipping toes into the water.  And I felt sad.
These past weeks haven't been a government funded Bank Holiday for me - in fact far from it.  And there are many who are in situations worse than mine.
What I feel most frustrated about is not the complexity of the decision
column2: but how the decision has (or has not) been communicated to us.  Leaders
column4: have a responsibility to the people that they lead and look after.  I understand that this is difficult.  I understand that there is no clear answer
column5: that nothing is guaranteed.  I understand that things need to change
column7: that I need to take care and be sensible.  But there are ways to communicate complexity that work.  Ask doctors who have to explain complicated diagnoses every day.

column2: one that works in A&E wrote this last night and it resonated far more for me:

column1: There are rarely clearly ‚Äúright or wrong‚Äù decisions in medicine. They often lay in shades of grey. However
column2: the worst decision is one that patients don‚Äôt understand
column3: don‚Äôt believe or cannot trust. I felt like that patient last night . Today I‚Äôm not watching the news and it‚Äôs a bit better.
